        detail: "Singapore's only landfill — Pulau Semakau, an offshore island — was originally projected to last until 2045 but current waste generation rates may exhaust it by 2035. Singapore generates 7.4 million tonnes of waste annually, with a recycling rate of only 57% (2023), down from 61% in 2017. The Zero Waste Masterplan (2019) targets a 30% reduction in waste-to-landfill by 2030. Key measures include: mandatory food waste segregation for large commercial premises (2024), the Extended Producer Responsibility framework for packaging (2025), and the beverage container return scheme launching in 2025. The challenge is acute: Singapore cannot export waste (unlike larger countries) and has no space for additional landfills — it must solve the problem or face a genuine existential logistics crisis.",
        use: "FOR the urgency of environmental action: Singapore's waste problem is not abstract or distant — Semakau's finite capacity creates a hard deadline that concentrates policymaking in a way that diffuse global warming targets do not. FOR policy innovation under constraint: Singapore's geographic limitations force creative solutions (waste-to-energy incineration reduces waste volume by 90%, offshore landfill engineering). COUNTER: the declining recycling rate (61% → 57%) despite government campaigns suggests that awareness alone does not change behaviour — incentive structures and convenience matter more. COUNTER: Singapore's waste-to-energy incineration, while volume-reducing, still produces carbon emissions and toxic ash — it is a less-bad option, not a good one. COUNTER: the fundamental problem is consumption volume — policy measures target waste management rather than questioning the growth model that generates the waste.",
