        use: "FOR UBI as effective policy: evidence from Finland, Kenya, and Stockton consistently shows improved wellbeing, no laziness effect, and in some cases increased employment — contradicting the main theoretical objection. FOR the comparison between universal and targeted approaches: Singapore's Workfare model (income supplement conditional on working) vs UBI (unconditional) represents a genuine philosophical debate about the role of the state. FOR evidence-based policy: these are randomised controlled trials, not ideology — the data should inform the debate. COUNTER: trial conditions do not replicate universal implementation — participants knew the trial was temporary, which limits behavioural conclusions. COUNTER: fiscal sustainability is untested — no country has implemented UBI at national scale; Finland's trial cost €20M for 2,000 people, scaling to 5.5 million would cost €60+ billion annually. COUNTER: Singapore's targeted approach is more fiscally efficient — resources go to those who need them most, not to the wealthy who would receive UBI payments they don't need.",
